<section class="section">
  <div class="section-inner">
    <div class="sec-eyebrow">What Whipple's involves</div>
    <h2 class="sec-h"><span class="te-content">Whipple's Procedure — <em>నేను చెప్పేది</em></span><span class="en-content">Whipple&rsquo;s Procedure — <em>What I tell patients</em></span></h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <div class="te-block">
        <p>Whipple's Procedure (medical name: pancreaticoduodenectomy) pancreatic head, duodenum, gallbladder, bile duct portion, మరియు regional lymph nodes remove చేసే major surgery. తరువాత 3 anastomoses తో digestive tract reconstruct చేస్తాను. Typically 6-8 hours, 7-10 day hospital stay.</p>
        <p>నేను AIIMS లో M.Ch training లో ఈ procedure regularly perform చేశాను. High-volume tertiary centre training అంటే cases volume తో experience వస్తుంది. ISGPS (International Study Group on Pancreatic Surgery) guidelines follow చేస్తాను.</p>
        <p>Published data: low-volume centres లో Whipple's mortality 10-15%, high-volume specialised centres లో 2-3%. ఇది surgeon choice లో important consideration. Honestly చెప్పాలంటే, ఏ surgeon దగ్గరైనా annual Whipple's volume అడగడం patient's right.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="en-block">
        <p>Whipple's Procedure (pancreaticoduodenectomy) removes the pancreatic head, duodenum, gallbladder, a portion of the bile duct and regional lymph nodes. The digestive tract is then reconstructed with three anastomoses. Typically 6-8 hours, 7-10 day hospital stay.</p>
        <p>I performed this procedure regularly during my M.Ch training at AIIMS. High-volume tertiary centre training means experience comes with case volume. I follow ISGPS (International Study Group on Pancreatic Surgery) guidelines.</p>
        <p>Published data shows Whipple's mortality at low-volume centres is 10-15%, compared to 2-3% at high-volume specialised centres. That is an important consideration in choosing a surgeon. To be honest, asking any surgeon for their annual Whipple's volume is your right as a patient.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
<section class="section section-grey">
  <div class="section-inner">
    <div class="sec-eyebrow">Indications</div>
    <h2 class="sec-h"><span class="te-content">Whipple's <em>ఎవరికి అవసరం</em></span><span class="en-content">Who needs <em>Whipple&rsquo;s Procedure</em></span></h2>
    <div class="proc-list">
      <div class="proc-item"><div class="proc-tier">1</div><div class="proc-body"><h4>Pancreatic Head Cancer</h4><p>Resectable adenocarcinoma in the head of the pancreas. Only 15-20% of pancreatic cancers are upfront resectable. Neoadjuvant chemotherapy with FOLFIRINOX or gemcitabine-nab-paclitaxel for borderline/locally advanced cases first.</p><div class="proc-meta">ISGPS Guidelines · NCCN</div></div></div>
      <div class="proc-item"><div class="proc-tier">2</div><div class="proc-body"><h4>Periampullary Cancers</h4><p>Cancers of the ampulla of Vater, distal bile duct or duodenum. Generally better prognosis than pancreatic adenocarcinoma after Whipple's.</p></div></div>
      <div class="proc-item"><div class="proc-tier">3</div><div class="proc-body"><h4>Pancreatic Neuroendocrine Tumours (PNETs)</h4><p>PNETs in the head of the pancreas. Surgical outcomes generally better than adenocarcinoma.</p></div></div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
<section class="section">
  <div class="section-inner">
    <div class="sec-eyebrow">Recovery timeline</div>
    <h2 class="sec-h"><span class="te-content">Whipple's తరువాత <em>Recovery</em></span><span class="en-content"><em>Recovery</em> After Whipple&rsquo;s</span></h2>
    <div class="proc-list">
      <div class="proc-item"><div class="proc-tier">1</div><div class="proc-body"><h4>Days 1-3 — ICU</h4><p>Intensive monitoring, pain management, fluid balance and drain surveillance.</p></div></div>
      <div class="proc-item"><div class="proc-tier">2</div><div class="proc-body"><h4>Days 4-7 — Ward</h4><p>Mobilisation starts. Gradual oral intake from clear liquids to soft foods. Bowel function monitoring.</p></div></div>
      <div class="proc-item"><div class="proc-tier">3</div><div class="proc-body"><h4>Days 7-10 — Discharge</h4><p>Once oral intake is adequate and pain is managed orally. Detailed discharge instructions provided.</p></div></div>
      <div class="proc-item"><div class="proc-tier">4</div><div class="proc-body"><h4>Weeks 2-8 — Home</h4><p>Gradual diet expansion. Pancreatic enzyme supplements often needed. Adjuvant chemotherapy discussion at 6-8 weeks if indicated.</p></div></div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>


